          "title": "Incomparability and the anatomy of idol-making (46:5-7)",
          "body": "The rhetorical question of verse 5 — 'To whom would you liken Me and make Me equal?' — functions as a courtroom challenge that presupposes its own answer. Isaiah then provides the empirical demonstration in verses 6-7: watch the idol being made. The worshiper lavishes gold from his purse, weighs silver on a scale, hires a craftsman, and the result is an object that must be lifted onto a shoulder, set in place, and — most damning — stands there and does not move (46:7). The Hebrew word mush — it does not budge from its spot — is the final stroke. A god that cannot move from where someone set it cannot respond to prayer, cannot advance to rescue, cannot do anything. When someone cries to it, it cannot answer (un, 46:7). When someone needs deliverance, it cannot save (yasha). The anatomy of idol-making is the anatomy of self-deception: the worshiper funds the god, makes the god, carries the god, and then expects the god to help him. The logical incoherence is complete. John Calvin comments on this passage that the idolater is 'worshiping his own work' — the creature's labor has become the creator's substitute. The chapter does not argue philosophically against this; it observes it and lets the observation carry the weight."
