          "title": "Stubborn-mindedness and the nearness of righteousness (46:12-13)",
          "body": "The chapter's final address targets the most resistant audience: 'the stubborn-minded, who are far from righteousness' (46:12). The Hebrew abbir lev — mighty of heart, stout-hearted — is an image of hardened obstinacy, the heart that cannot be moved by the evidence already presented. Their distance from righteousness (tsedaqah) is not geographical but dispositional; they have refused what God has been moving toward them throughout the chapter. God's response to this obstinacy is not withdrawal but advance: 'I bring near My righteousness, it is not far off; and My salvation will not delay' (46:13). The syntax is striking — the subject is God, the verb is God's action, the movement is entirely from God's side. The stubborn-minded need not close the distance because God is closing it. This is not universalism; the passage ends with the naming of a specific place — 'I will grant salvation in Zion, and My glory for Israel' — anchoring the gift in the covenant community. But the structure of verse 13 is significant for Pauline theology: righteousness that the human being cannot reach is brought near by God's own initiative. The apostle Paul's language in Romans 3:21-22 — 'the righteousness of God has been manifested apart from the Law … through faith in Jesus Christ' — follows the same structure: righteousness arrives, it is not earned. Isaiah 46:13 is, in embryo, what Galatians and Romans will expound fully."
