    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what the text says to what it means — discerning Isaiah's intent in his original setting and tracing the canonical resonance of his argument. Isaiah 46 is located in the theological heart of the Book of Comfort (chs. 40-55), where the prophet addresses exilic Israel with the certainty of Babylon's fall and God's redemptive return. The chapter's argument is tightly integrated: satirical narration (vv. 1-2) grounds theological contrast (vv. 3-4), which enables the incomparability challenge (v. 5), which the manufacturing scene demonstrates empirically (vv. 6-7), which the memory-imperatives then mobilize (vv. 8-11), issuing in the pastoral announcement of imminent salvation (vv. 12-13). Four movements follow that argument.",
