        "body": "The rhetorical pivot at verse 3 is the chapter's pastoral core. The 'Listen to Me' (*shama*, imperative) signals a direct divine address, and what follows is one of the most concentrated expressions of God's covenant commitment in the Hebrew prophets. The contrast with verses 1-2 is constructed through identical vocabulary: the same verbs that described the idol being carried (nasa, saval) now describe God carrying Israel. This is not coincidence; it is Isaiah's argument. The structural antithesis forces the comparison: choose the god who is carried, or the God who carries.\n\nThe scope of God's carrying is defined by two temporal poles: 'from birth' and 'from the womb' (v. 3) on one end; 'to your old age' and 'to your graying years' (v. 4) on the other. The entire human lifespan is bracketed within God's covenantal faithfulness. The address to 'the remnant of the house of Israel' is significant — by Isaiah's time and certainly by the exilic period, a remnant-theology had developed in which the preserved, chastened core of the people rather than the full nation would be the vessel of God's continuing purposes (cf. Isaiah 10:20-22; Romans 9:27). God's carrying is not contingent on Israel's fullness or strength; it is directed to those who remain.\n\nThe fourfold pledge of verse 4 — 'I have done it, I will carry you, I will bear you, I will deliver you' — accumulates like a covenantal signature. The perfect tense 'I have done it' grounds every future promise in an already-accomplished past. The repetition of nasa and saval before the climactic malat (deliver) is a deliberate rhetorical building — John Oswalt (*The Book of Isaiah: Chapters 40-66*, NICOT) notes that this is the chapter's 'theological center of gravity,' the answer to both the idol-polemic and the fear of the exile. Charles Spurgeon, preaching on this passage, observed that the God who carried you when you could not carry yourself will not set you down when you are old enough to be embarrassed by it. The covenant runs to the end.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nasa* = to lift and carry (used of bearing burdens, carrying children, and lifting sacrifices — all senses hover here). *Saval* = to bear a heavy load, with the connotation of patient endurance under weight — the same word used of the Suffering Servant who 'bore our griefs' (53:4). *Malat* (deliver, cause to escape) is the word for military rescue and personal deliverance — it answers the idol's failure in v. 2 directly."
