        "excerpt": "To whom would you liken Me and make Me equal and compare Me, that we would be alike?… Remember the former things long past, for I am God, and there is no other… Declaring the end from the beginning.",
        "body": "The incomparability challenge of verse 5 ('To whom would you liken Me?') has deep roots in the Hebrew prophetic tradition — Isaiah 40:18, 25 asked the same question; here it appears after the specific idol-demolition of verses 6-7, where the manufacturing scene provides the empirical answer: the only candidate for comparison is a manufactured object that cannot move or speak. The challenge functions not as an open inquiry but as a rhetorical verdict: no comparison is possible, and the idol-making scene is the proof.\n\nThe instruction to 'remember the former things long past' (46:9) is the chapter's epistemological pivot. The Hebrew *zakhar* is not merely cognitive recall but the active, volitional bringing-to-mind of God's past acts for present purposes. What is to be remembered is the 'former things' (*rishon*) — a technical term in Isaiah 40-55 for the prior saving acts of God (the Exodus, the wilderness provision, the conquest) that constitute the evidentiary base for trusting the new acts now announced (the return from exile, the call of Cyrus). The logic is: if you have seen what God has done, you have sufficient grounds for believing what He says He will do. Tim Keller notes that this is the structure of biblical faith throughout — not blind trust but evidence-based confidence in a God whose track record is verifiable.\n\nThe declaration of verse 10 — 'declaring the end from the beginning' — is one of Isaiah's most precise statements of divine omniscience. *Nagad* (to declare, announce publicly) paired with *acharit* (end, latter things) and *reshit* (beginning) creates a temporal frame that spans all of history. God does not predict the future by extrapolation from the present; He announces it because He inhabits it. The corollary is verse 11: the 'bird of prey from the east' — Cyrus, already named in 44:28 and 45:1 — is not a human leader who happened to serve God's purposes but a man specifically called ('calling,' *qara*) for God's plan (*etsah*). The twin emphatic particles in verse 11 — 'truly I have spoken; truly I will bring it to pass; I have planned it; surely I will do it' — function as a divine seal on the announcement. What God has spoken, He performs; what He has planned, He executes without exception.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nagad* (declare, announce) is a public-disclosure verb — it implies bringing hidden things into the open. *Etsah* (purpose, counsel) is the divine sovereign plan that cannot be thwarted (cf. Isaiah 14:26-27 where the same word governs the immovable divine intention). *Ayit* (bird of prey) is a raptor — swift, swooping, lethal — a military metaphor for Cyrus's campaign style. The 'from a far country' (*merchaq*) echoes 39:3 where Hezekiah admitted Babylon was 'from a far country'; now God summons His instrument from that same far horizon."
