        "body": "The final address of the chapter sharpens the pastoral tension to its most acute point. The audience is not pagans but Israelites — 'stubborn-minded' (*abbir lev*, mighty-hearted, stout-hearted) people who have remained unconvinced by the evidence of verses 1-11. They are 'far from righteousness' — not because righteousness is distant in principle, but because they have positioned themselves away from it through unbelief and moral hardening. The exilic context suggests these are Israelites who have either accommodated Babylonian religion or simply lost hope that God would act, a despair that functions practically as idolatry.\n\nGod's response is entirely counterintuitive: He brings righteousness *near* rather than calling the stubborn-minded to travel toward it. The verb *qarav* (to bring near, to cause to approach) is an active divine initiative — the distance between the stubborn human and the righteous God is closed from God's side. This is the chapter's most theologically pregnant moment, and its New Testament resonance is substantial. Paul's argument in Romans 3:21-26 follows the same logic: 'the righteousness of God has been manifested apart from the Law … through faith in Jesus Christ for all those who believe.' The righteousness that human beings cannot manufacture or reach, God brings near through His own action — in Isaiah, through the Cyrus-redemption and the return from exile; in Paul, through the cross and resurrection of Jesus Christ. The fuller sense (*sensus plenior*) of Isaiah 46:13 is not merely the return from Babylon but the final righteousness that arrives in the person of Christ.\n\nThe concluding specificity — 'I will grant salvation in Zion, and My glory (*tiphara*h) for Israel' — grounds the announcement in historical and geographical concreteness. Salvation is not a state of feeling but a gift installed in a place and given to a people. The word *tipharah* (splendor, glory, beauty) appears in Exodus 28:2 for the garments of the high priest — it is the radiance of God's presence manifesting in the created order. That glory, once partially visible in the tabernacle and temple, is here promised as the destiny of restored Israel. The chapter ends with an image of arrival and installation, not merely of journey and hope.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Abbir lev* (stubborn-minded) is literally 'mighty of heart' — the same adjective used of God's power elsewhere; here it denotes a heart so fortified against God that even His power cannot penetrate except by grace. *Tsedaqah* (righteousness) in the prophetic corpus frequently carries the full weight of covenantal faithfulness — God acting rightly on behalf of His people in a way that both expresses and demonstrates His character. *Teshuah* (salvation, deliverance) is related to the root *yasha* — the same root as Jesus's name (Yeshua). The echo is not accidental in the canon's full perspective."
